    "media:imagetext": "Great Western Champagne.\nAmerica's oldest continuous champagne winery. Named as\nthe \"Great\" champagne of the \"Western world. Founded\n1860 - U.S. Bonded Winery #1.\nFrankfurters.\nReputedly came from Frankfurt, Germany and introduced to\nthis country in the 1880's by a Bavarian gentleman who sold\nthem together with a pair of cotton gloves to prevent his cus-\ntomers from burning their fingers.\nPoached Fillets of Sole Diamond Jim.\nDiamond Jim started out as the son of a poor saloon keeper\nand rose to be a wealthy man as a pioneer of the railroad era.\nA man who showed his wealth through wearing ornate dia-\nmond jewelry and gifting his friends and associates with the\nsame. A man whose girth was matched only by his incredible\nappetite for gourmet foods.\nSourdough Rolls.\nPossibly the oldest of bread recipes dating as far back as 4000\nB.C. It is made with a sourdough \"starter,\" a self perpetuat-\ning yeast mixture made with a combination of flour, sugar\nand water. It became identified in America through its use by\nthe Alaskan sourdoughs, prospectors who carried \"starters\"\nstrapped to their packs so that they could make bread any-\ntime without having to walk to the nearest town.\nWaldorf Salad.\nThe original recipe was created by one of the most famous\nof Maitres d'Hôtel, Oscar of the Waldorf.\nSalt Water Taffy.\nThis candy, almost a tradition is sold along the boardwalk\nat Atlantic City. Rumor has it that it is made with sea water.\nCover.\nOne of a series of photographs depicting Early 19th Century\ncooking utensils from New England, in wood, tin, ceramic,\ncast and handwrought iron.",
